      "statement": "dopamine_hyperactivity_hypothesis outranks nmda_hypofunction_hypothesis in the cites_as_support layer. This tests whether institutional commitment to the dominant paradigm suppresses a mechanistically richer alternative in the citation network. The NMDA hypothesis (Olney, Coyle) provides superior explanatory coverage: it explains positive symptoms (via downstream dopamine disinhibition), negative symptoms, and cognitive deficits -- everything the dopamine hypothesis explains plus what it cannot. It is also mechanistically upstream (NMDA hypofunction causes the dopamine excess detected by PET). Despite this, the NMDA hypothesis has not generated approved treatments, and APA/WFSBP guidelines do not cite it as the primary theoretical basis for antipsychotic prescribing. Prediction: in the citation layer, the dopamine hypothesis outranks the NMDA hypothesis in hub centrality, reflecting institutional commitment to the treatment-validated paradigm over the mechanistically more complete but therapeutically unresolved alternative. If confirmed: this is a structural signature of dominant-paradigm suppression -- the same pattern as monoamine_hypothesis suppressing non-monoamine evidence in M_MED1."
